{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_kendall_ver01/data/sn82014085/00393346814/1945082001/0595.xml":{"full_text":"SECOND SECTION\nPAGES 9 TO 16\nTHE WATERBURY DEMOCRAT. WATERBURY, CONN.. MONDAY. AUGUST 20. 1945\nRush to Cash'\nBonds Flayed\ni By Jim Moran\nBillions Needed\nNext 6 Months\nTo Maintain Gl's\nWarning the heavy cashing of\nbonds at this time would nedanger\nour national' economic stability,\nJames E. Moran, chairman of the\nWar Finance Committee, today\nurged bond buyers to hold their\nbonds to consolidate Victory and as\nsure our fighting men a return to a\ncountry of sound economy. Mr. Mo\nran further asserted bond reserves\nshould be held for the individual\u2019s\n\u25a0welfare because of the uncertainty\nof the period of reconversion.\nPointing to the fact that billions\nof dollars will be required within the\nnext six months to wind up the war\neffort, the War Finance Chairman\ndeclared:\n\"The problem of financing the\nwar is still acute. There are mil\nlions of our men overseas who must\nbe returned to this country and mil\nlions more who must be retained\nwith armies of occupation. Billions\nof dollars will be required to main\ntain them and billions more to pro\nvide them with mustering out pay.\nAll this costs money.\n\u201cIn the last war, the government\nspent more money in the six months\nfollowing the Armistice than it did\nduring the last six months of fight\ning.\n\u201cOther billions of dollars will be\nrequired to provide for contract\nterminations and to meet Other\ncosts Incidental to the completion of\nour war effort.\n\"To make secure the Victory that\nhas been accomplished at the cost\nof so many lives, we must maintain\nlarge forces of occupation ih Ger\nmany and Japanese territory.\nMounting expenditures will require\nthe support of the individual in our\npost war effort as they did during\nthe years of conflict.\u201d\n\u201cOur national stability can best\nbe advanced at this time by care\nful spending and cotninued invest\nment in bonds. Further infla\ntionary trends, which follow on the\nheels of war, and which cause wide\nspread hardships, can only be\naverted by these methods.\u201d\nLate Realty\nNews\nThe fllowing documents have been\nfiled at the office of Town Clerk\nMary C. Kilmartin:\nWarranty Deeds\nFloyd H. Rasmussen and Wesley\nS. Rasmussen to William J. Ar\nquett and Berdetta H. Arquett,\nproperty on Anna avenue.\nFloyd H. Rasmussen and Wesley\nS. Rasmussen to Benedict J. Latizas\nand Anna Mary Latozas, property\non Anna avenue.\nFloyd H. Rasmussen and Wesley\nS. Rasmussen to William H. Midg\nley and Annabella Midgley, prperty\non Anna avenue.\nKurt E. Shemenske to Helen\nLuddy, property on North Main\nstreet.\nExecutor\u2019s Deed\nThe Citizens Manufacturers\nNational Bank, executor unde rthe\nwill of Ida M. Lewis to Daniel C.\nRyan, two pieces of property on\nSouth Main street.\nKurte E. Shemenske and Ruby\nN. Shemenske to the Thomaston\nSavings Bank, property on Bucks\nHill Road. $4,000.\nRelease of Mortgages\nNaugatuck Savings Bank to Floyd\nH. Rasmussen and Wesley S. Ras\nmussen. lots 32, 65, 60, 59, 61, Anna\navenue.\nQuit Claim Deeds\nCharles J. Shortt to Kurt E. She\nmenske, property on North Main\nstreet.\nCharles E. Kelly to Rocco Famig\nlietti, property on Clamatis ave\nnue.\nFrank Tavano to Joseph Tavano,\nproperty on Scovill street.\nJohn Vaccarelli to Raffaela Vac\ncarelli, property on Benefit street.\nMortgage Deeds\nRobert M. Schwartz to the Thom\naston Savings Bank, property on\nCooke street, $8,500.\nWilliam J. Arquett and Berdetta\nH. Arquett to the Naugatuck Sav\nings bank, property on Anna ave\nnue. $5,100.\nBenedict J. Latozas and Anna\nMary Latozas to the Naugatuck\nSavings Bank, property on Anna\navenue, $5,100.\nWilliam H. Midgley and Anna\nbella Midgley to Naugatuck Savings\nBank, property on Anna avenue, $5,\nW0.\nFloyd H. Rasmussen and Wesley\nRasmussen to the Naugatuck Sav\nings Bank, property on Anna ave\nnue. $5,100\nFloyd H. Rassmussen and Wesley\nS. Rasmussen to Naugatuck Sav\nings bank, property on Anne ave\nnue. $5,100.\nPA.H-.xmb\nFloyd H. Rasmussen and Wesley\nS Rasmussen to the Naugatuck\nSavings bank, property on Anna\navenue, $5,100.\nAward Honor Medal\nTo Boston Officer\nBoston. Aug. 20.\u2014(UP)\u2014The Dis\ntinguished Service Medal has been\nawarded to Brig Oen. Calvin De\nWitt, Jr., commander of the Boston\nport of embarkation and former\ndeputy commander of the New York\nport of embarkation, for \u201coutstand\ning leadership and skill.**\nA native of Fort Leavenworth.\nKans.. D' Witt was cited by the\nWar Department for \u201cfar-sighted\nplanning and judgment in expedit\ning shipments of troopa and suppllti\nto the overseas theaters.\n\u201cWhile terving as deputy port\ncommander at New York, ne de\nvised numerous procedural inno\nvations which reaulted in vastly In\ncreased operational efficiency as well\nas greatly enhanced utilisation of\nexisting facilities during a period\nof continuous expansion.\n\u201cAssigned as eommanding gen\neral. Boson port of embarkation, In\nHumanity Pays Terrible Toll For World War II\n1\n2,700.000\n1,070,000\nL350,000\nGERMANY\nPOLAND\n(exterminated)\nCHINA\nJAPAN\nYUGOSLAVIA\nBRITISH EMPIRE\nITALY\nUNITED STATES\nFRANCE\nPOLAND\n000\n12\n500\n000\n700\n000\n000\n000\n430\n000\n30\n000\n166\nTOTAL\n55.743\n(military)\nAUSTRIA\nROMANIA\nGREECE\nHUNGARY\n\u201cSLAVES\"\nHOLLAND\n-K\"\nFINLAND\nBELGIUM\nCZECHOSLOVAKIA\nPHILIPPINES\nThe tabulation above gives the terrible price that the war cost the peoples of the world in lives lost and\nwrecked. The figures include military and civilian losses. They are taken from the most conservative\nbut incomplete estimates from official statistics, and show that over 50,000,000 people are dead, wounded\nand missing. In addition, there are 12,000,000 prisoners of war and, as the war ends, to this figure can be\nadded over 4,000,000 more\u2014Japan\u2019s armed forces.\nChinese Take\n24-Jap Held\nTowns\nBY GEORGE WANG\nUnited Press Staff Correspondent\nChungking, Aug. 20 UP)\nMarshal Chiang Kai-shek\u2019s Chinese\narmies recaptured 20 enemy-held\ntowns during the past 24 hours, it\nwas announced today, as Gen.\nYasuji Okamura, Japanese com\nmander-in-chief in China informed\nChiang that he was prepared to\nfollow surrender instructions.\nOkamura, replying to the Marsh\nal's third telegram, said that he\nwas obeying orders for a Japanese\ndelegation to arrive at Chihkiang\nairfield on Tuesday morning for\nsurrender terms.\nJap Position Unknown\nThere was no indication whether\nthe Japanese were\u00bb resisting the\nChinese advances, but apparently\nthey were only marking time until\nthe surrender terms are completed.\nGen. Tang En-Po\u2019s troops re\ncaptured Taiyuan, in Northern\nShanshi province, while Gen. Hu\nTsung-Nan\u2019s forces retook Shenh\nsien in Western Honan province.\nGen. Fu Cho-Yi. governor des\nignate of Suiyuan province, re\ncaptured Paotow, in Western Sui\nyuan.\nA fourth Chinese army recaptured\nNinghai, Fenshui, Wuhing, Tahtsin,\nTsungteh, Tunglu and linan in\nChekiang province and Sunfeng in\nKiangsi province.\nOther Towns Taken\nOther units of the same army\nreentered Yungtsi, Lintsin and\nYungho in Southwest Shansi, and\nChenghsien and Hsiangshan, in\nEastern Chekpang.\nMarshal Yen Hsi-Shan, comman\nder of the Chinese 61st army and\nChiang\u2019s governor designate of\nShansi province, recaptured Ling\nfen, Yuncheng. Hungtung and\nChaocheng in Southern Shansi.\nA Chinese government spokesman\ncalled Yen\u2019s performance the most\ndramatic of all and recalled that\nthe Communist Yenan radio claimed\nseveral days ago that Yen had\njoined the Japanese.\nThe Peiping underground radio\nreported that Gen. Fu Cho-Yi and\nhis central government troops had\nentered Peiping on Saturday night\nwithout a fight.\nCurtail Building\nOf 135 Ships\nWashington, Aug. 20.\u2014(UP)\u2014The\nMaritime Commission today an\nnounced cancellation of $425,000,000\nin contracts covering construction of\n135 ships. Three contracts for\nspecial military equipment were in\ncluded in the cancellations.\nThe ship cancellations included\n35 coastal cargo ships of the C-I\nM-AV-1 type, 42 Victory cargo ships,\n24 coastal tankers for lend lease to\nGreat Britain, four Liberty ships\nbeing converted to aircraft rapair\nshops, eight military type Victory\nships, eight tankers, five C-4 mili\ntary transports, six refrigerator ships\nand three P-2 military transports.\n$70 Million Cancellation\nThe three contracts tor special\nmilitary equipment, which was in\ntended for the Navy, accounted for\n$70,000,000 for the total cancella\ntions.\nThe cancellations affected three\nyards and vessels:\nLend lease tankers\u2014New Englumi\nShipbuilding Corp., South Portland.\nMe 13.\nAircraft repair ships (Liberty)\u2014\nNew England Shipbuilding Corp.,\nSouth Portland, Me., four.\nVictory cargo ships\u2014Bethlehem\nPa'rfleld Shipyard, Inc.. Palrrield.\nMe 33.\nBUILOINO PERMITS\nLate Bulletins\nPEARL HARBOR PROBE CONTINUES\nWashington, Aug. 20\u2014(UP)\u2014Former Supreme Court\nJustice Owen J. Roberts, who headed the secret investiga\ntion of the Pearl Harbor disaster, and Secretary of State\nJames F. Byrnes conferred for 20 minutes with President\nTruman today.\nARMY-NAVY FOOTBALL GAME\nWest Point, N. Y., Aug. 20\u2014(UP)\u2014The annual Army\nNavy football game will be played at Philadelphia\u2019s Munici\npal stadium on Dec. 1, Col. Lawrence (Biff) Jones, Army\ngraduate manager of athletics, announced today.\nTWO INJURED IN STRIKE\nStamford, Aug. 20\u2014(UP)\u2014Two girls, one a striker and\nanother a worker at the Plastic Manufacturers, Inc., were\ninjured today during incidents at the concern\u2019s two plants.\nNAUGATUCK FLOOD CONTROL\nWashington, Aug. 20\u2014(UP)\u2014U. S. Army engineers to\nday prepared to swing into a gigantic program of flood con\ntrol and river and harbor improvements that were postponed\nduring the war. One of these possibly include the Nauga\ntuck river valley program opposed by many.\nU. S. COMMISSION FOR GREECE\nWashington, Aug. 20\u2014(UP)\u2014The United States re\nvealed today that it will send a special commission to Greece\nto help supervise the forthcoming election there and \u201cto\naid in securing the free expression, by secret ballot, of the\nwill of the Greek people.\u201d\nWAGE ADJUSTMENT RULES\nWashington, Aug. 20\u2014(UP)\u2014Chairman George W.\nTaylor of the War Labor Board said today that the board\n\u201cnow has the right to order\u201d wage adjustments necessary\nto remove inequities hampering reconversion, \u201cThe Little\nSteel Formula and wage brackets not withstanding.\u201d\nPROTEST ATOMIC BOMB\nNew York, Aug. 20\u2014(UP)\u2014Thirty-four church and\neducational leaders sent a statement today to President\nTruman, expressing their \u201cunmitigated condemnation of\nthe use of atomic bombs against Japan.\nUNDERGROUND CITIES\nNew York, Aug. 20\u2014(UP)\u2014A world of vast under\nground cities\u2014the only kind safe from atomic bombs\u2014was\nenvisioned today by Louis Bruchiss, research engineer and\nauthority on aircraft armament.\nBond Drive\nPrizes Here\nNot Claimed\n15, Including Car\nWinner, Tardy\nClaims Moran\nFifteen prizes, including a Chev\nrolet automobile, drawn in the Sev\nenth War Loan prize award August\n2 have not yet been clalmsd by the\nlucky stub holders at the War Fin\nance office, Leavenworth street.\nJames E. Moran, chairman, stated\nthis morning.\nThe 100 persons who won prizes\ntotaling IIS,000 were notified by\nmall of their good fortune the\nmorning following the award. In\nmany Instanoes the name and ad\ndress shown on the stub was Inad\nequate and the War Finance office\nwas unable to contact them.\nThhough newspapers have previ\nously published the names of win\nners, Mr. Moran said this morning\nIt is becoming increasingly obvious\nmsny of the fifteen persons who\nhave not yet oalled for their prises\nhave not Isamed they were winners.\nHe therefore requested that if any\nof the following persons, whose ad\ndress listed below are Incomplete,\nare known to Dsmoerst readers Uutt\nItier be immediately notified to call\nat tits office at the Way\nM\nStub holders of the 15 prizes not\nyet claimed are: George Brenan,\nNaugatuck, Chevrolet car; I. Bour\ngeous (no address) and John Pan\narauskas, 201 Sunnyside avenue,\nmovie cameras; Gabe. 41 Manor ave\nnue. Kodak camera; Arthur Ouimet,\n51 Church street, and Olive R. New\nton, 54 Fiske street, candid cameras;\nElizabeth Nichols, 501 Piedmont St.,\nelectric range; J. Hastihgs (no ad\ndress) Ashing rod; Walter Wood, 145\nClinton street, airplane luggage:\nMaureen Holihan. 55 Brentwood\navenue, portable radio; Bowman\nBurke, Oakville, and M. Mancini\n(no address) table radios; Clara\nMeyer. Scovll employe, electric re\nfrigerator; M. Canlero (no address)\nSchick shaver; and V. Archambault.\nB Glenridge street, washing machine.\nReduce Draft\nCalls for Sept.\nWashington, Aug. 30\u2014(UP)\u2014The\nNavy announced today It has low\nered Its September draft call from\n33.000 to 13,000 for the Navy and\nMarine Corps.\nThe original schedule oalled for\n17.000 men for the Navy and 3,000\nfor the Marines. This has been re\nduced to 10.000 fo rthe Navy and\n3.000 for the Marines.\nPredict Many\nTemporary\nLayoffs\nForesee Speedy\nReconversion\nFor Nation\nBoston, Aug. 20 (UP> The\nUnited Business Service predicts\nthat 7,000,000 workers will oe unem\nployed within the next six to right\nmonths.\n\"However, large numbers of war\nworkers, especially women, will leave\nthe labor market,\u201d the Service said,\n\u2018\u2018and the service Industries will ab\nsorb a substantial number of work\ners.\n\"Neve> thelss, unemployment; will\nagain become a major homefront\nproblem\nSpecial Survey\nIn a special report on the post\nV-J day business outlook, the serv\nice also predicted:\n1. War production will be cut\nrapidly from a rate of about $50,\n000,000,000 to $12,000,000,000 a year.\n2. Reconversion \"will be relative\nly speedy.\" Limited quantities oi\nautomobiles, refrigerators and\nother consumer durable goods will\nreach markets by the fourth quar\nter.\n3. A \u201creal boom\u201d is cxpectec. in\nthe building industry but it will not\nget underway fully until next\nspring.\n4. Retail sales will tend \u2018t'o\nslacken moderately in reflection of\nwar plant layoffs and tend\nency to wait for better-quality\ngoods.\u201d\n5. Commodity prices \u201cwill show\nmarked irregularities.\u201d\n6. Pew production controls will\nremain except on scarce materials\nand \"to prevent hogging of ma\nterials by a few big firms.\u201d\n7. Earnings will decline but tax\n\u201ccarry-backs and excess profits\ntaxes will cushion the impact of\nrather sharp declines in before-tax\nprofits.\u201d\nPeace Theme\nOf Sermons\nChurches Unite\nIn Thanksgiving\nPrayers were offered Sunday in\nall churches of the city in Thanks\ngiving for victory and hope for a\nlasting peace. The topic of sermons\nembraced this subject.\nThe Gospel of the Sunday as\npointed out by Rev. Francis P.\nBratton, assistant at St. Margaret's\nchurch, as well as preachers in\nother churches was timely, citing\nthe story of the ten lepers healed,\nand only one returning to give\nthanks to Almighty God.\nRev. Thomas L. Sinclair, rector\nof All Souls\u2019 Episcopal church spoke\nat the morning service and at the\nevening union service for all Pro\ntestant churches.\nRev. John J. Snavely, pastor of\nthe First Methodist church spoke\non \u201cThe Treasure of the Kingdom\u201d\nat a union service of the First\nMethodist and First Congregational\nchurches in the morning.\nRabbi David Polish of Temple Is\nrael spoke on new responsibilities\narising out of the war. and Rabbi\nWilliam P. Greenfeld lead special\nprayer services at the Beth-el\nsynagogue.\nOther churches, both Catholic\nand Protestant, held special services.\nFather Bratton of St. Margaret\u2019s\nurged all parishioners to spend one\nhour this week in their church of\nfering prayers of thanksgiving.\nSocieties of Our Lady of Mount\nCarmel church held processions\nthrough the Town Plot section yes\nterday afternoon, parishioners and\nfriends joining in this testimony of\nthanksgiving.\nHome Front\nView Today\nWashlngon, Aug. 20.\u2014(UP)\u2014The\nhome front picture as it looks to\nday:\nPood\u2014Cheese and canned fish ex\npected next off the ration list. Re\nduction of practically all red point\nvalues for meat due in September\nand termination of meat rationing\nexpected later.\nShoes\u2014End of rationing expected\nwithin two months, possibly as early\nas two weeks.\nClothing\u2014Long-scarce items due\nback on market soon as result of\nmilitary release of huge amounts\nof textiles.\nWages\u2014War Labor Board super\nvision continued but only limit on\nincreases henceforth is that they\nmust not result in price increases.\nPrices\u2014OPA ordered by President\nTruman to continue vigilant price\nceilings to prevent inflation.\nReconversion\u2014WPB to announce\ntoday revocation of 80 or more of\nits 400 orders controlling industry\nand materials.\nNaval Box Score\nu.s.\nJAPAN\nIATTLISHIPS\n10\nAIRCRAFT CARRIERS\nII\n17\nCRUISERS\n10\nDESTROYERS\nl*S\nDESTROYER-ESCORTS\nSURMARINES\nU\nTOTALS I I4f *>14\nTtawtriw Nwra ti Imm to Mm\nmTSJh'inns. nvTvi\nMANCH\nKOREA\nJAPAN\nGUAM\nPHILIPPINES\nUncle Sam Had Plenty Up His Sleeve\nT SUPER SUPERFORTR\nV\nHINA\nPacific Ocean\nHAWAIIAN i$\nNEW\nGUINEA\nMaximum range of B 29\u2014 1800 m\n{Shown by broken line;\nEstimated range of new super brm;\n2*2 to 3 times greater, 4500 to 54\ni (Shown by solid lines\nThe atom bomb was far from being the only new weapon Uncle\nhad up his sleeve at war's end, according to Gen. Henry H. Arnold,\nU. S. Air Forces chief, who revealed a new snper-dooper bomlirr\nwhose range makes B-29 Superforts seem like something for local\nwhistle-stop run. The new bomber, so far unnamed, could cover all of\nAsia, the Pacific and Atlantic from bases now held by the U. 8. With\nrange two-and-a-half to three times the range of the B-29 shown in\npicto-map above, it could fly from Hawaii to the China coast, complete\na bombing mission and return to its base. As shown at right, the\nsuper-super bomber could circle the earth at the equator\u201424,902 miles\n\u2014in three hops.\nHospital Bulletins\nGilbert Cronin, 5, 33 Warner\nplace son of Mr. and Mrs. John\nCronin, bitten by a dog. was\ntreated yesterday afternoon at\n3:05 at St. Mary's hospital.\nAlfred Sciarra, 13. 38 Ash street,\nwas treated at St. Mary's hospital\nlast evening for a lacerated lip\nreceived when he fell from a\npicket fence.\nAnthony Remokitis, 26, 7 Garden\nCircle was treated for lacerations\nof the skull, shoulders and right\nhip sustained when he was struck\n1 by a bus in Exchange Place this\nj morning. St. Mary\u2019s hospital au\nJ thprities reported.\nAdelia Gule. 22 months old\ndaughter of Mr. and Mrs. Jonus\nGule, 92 South Elm street, was\nadmitted to St. Mary\u2019s hospital\nthis morning and discharged after\nbeing struck by a car .in front of\nher home. The girl was not in\njured.\nWilliam Dulude, 21, 80 Sergeant\nstreet, Springfield, Mass., was\ntreated at St. Mary\u2019s hospital\nthis morning for injuries received\nwhen an 800 pound piece of lead\nfell from a truck he was un\nloading. He was treated for a\nseverely lacerated little finger.\nJaps Appeal\nTo Missioner\nLondon, Aug. 20.\u2014HIP)\u2014Tokyo\nradio today broadcast a long appeal\nattributed to the Rev. aPtri-k Byrn.\n59-year-old American Catholic mis\nsionary, calling upon American\ntroops to \u201cmtain strict discipline\nin their conduct\u201d when they land on\nJapan.\nFather Byrn was described as the\nvice-director of the Maryknol Cath\nolic Mission. He was said to be\nliving at Kyoto.\nMeet Commander\nHe was quoted as saying that he\ndesired to meet Gen. Douglas Mac\nArthur at the earliest possible mo\nment to \u201cexplain the mental strug\ngle and tense psychological situation\nprevailing among the Japanese peo\nple.\u201d\nThe Tokyo radio quoted Father\nByrn as saying that he believed \u201cthe\nmoment has come for him to work\nfor the peace and goodwill of his\ncountry, the United States, and for\nthe country where he has resided\nthe past 11 years, Japan, and for\nall mankind.\"\nLegion Post Plans\nBridgeport Reunion\nOpen house will be held Saturday,\nSept. 1, at the Harry W. Congdon\nAmerican Legion hall at 307 Gol\nden Hill street, Bridgeport, accord\ning to Frank Colangelo of 231 Eas\nton Avenue, this city, who was in\nformed of the event by James Cul\nlen, president of the 56th C. A. C.\nol Bridgeport.\nThe following day a reunion will\nbe held at Lenny's Wagon Wheel,\n711 Barnum Ave., Bridgeport Wa\nterbury will be well represented at\nboth events.\nSouth Amtricon\nStudonts Protest\nBuenos Aires, Aug. 20 (UPP>\u2014\nProfessors and students In Argen\ntine universities went on strike to\nday in protest against the govern\nment or President Edelmlro Far\nrell\nThe aignal for the strike was\nFarrell's return from a visit to\nParaguay During his absence, the\nrimment had been administered\nVice-President Juan D. Prron.\natrong man of the reigtme, who is\naccused by university and other\nliberal groups of seeking to become\npresident In elections scheduled lor\nneat year,\nJohn Russell, 35, Pemberton\nstreet, suffered lacerations of the\nleft eye when he was struck by\ntwo men early yesterday morning.\nHe was treated at St. Mary s\nhospital at 2 a. m. and there\nafter discharged.\nKenneth Roberg, 25, 825 Frost\nroad, was treated at St. Mary\u2019s\nhospital yesterday at 4 p. m. for\ninjuries received when he caught\nhis right eyelid on a fish hook\nwhile fishing.\nCatherine McCary, 3. daughter\nof Mr. and Mrs. George McCary.\n19 Pleasant street, was treated at\nSt. Mary\u2019s hospital for a lacer\nated forehead suffered when she\nfell on a cement walk in her\nback yard yesterday afternoon.\nShe was discharged after treat\nment.\nEdward Ranslow. 15, Sunnyside\navenue, akville, was admitted to\nWaterbury hospital yesterday aft\nernoon at 3:05 for injuries re\nceived when he fell from a truck\nin Middlebury when going around\na curve at Country Club road.\nLeroy Childs, two and a half\nyear old son of Mr. and Mrs. j\nLeroy Childs. 14 Meadow street, j\nwas admitted to St. Mary's hos- 1\npital last night suffering from a J\npossible fractured skull and lacer- j\nations of the nose and face sus\ntained when he was struck by a j\ncar on South Main street near\nMeadow street.\nMator Patrolman Joseph Mur\nphy said Daniel \u2019Connor, Straits\nTurnpike. Middlebury. driver of\nthe car, struck the child when he\ndarted out into the street in\nfront of O'Connor\u2019s vehicle.\nVeronica Joyce, 2, daughter of\nMr. and Mrs. John Joyce, 354 Tu\ndor street, was treated at St.\nMary\u2019s hospital yesterday after\noon for a knee injury suffered\nwhen she fell from a tricycle in\nfront of her home. She was dis\ncharged after treatment.\nYoungest Deans\nTake Office\nBoston. Aug. 20.\u2014(UP)\u20141Two of\nthe nation\u2019s youngest college presi\ndents assumed office today at Bos\nton and Holy Cross colleges.\nThe Rev. William L. Keleher, S.\nJ.. 39, was named last night to suc\nceec the Very Rev. William J. Mur\nphy. S. J.. as president of Bosotn\nCollege w,hile the Rev. William J.\nHealey. Sr.. 38. was appointed suc\ncessor to the Very Rev. Joseph R.\nN. Maxwell, S. ,T\u201e at Holy Cross.\nAnnounce Appointments\nThe Very Rev. John J. McEleney,\nS. J., provincial of the Society of\nJesus in New' England, announce\nthe appointments but he did not\ndisclose the new assignments of\nFather Murphy and Maxwell, who\nserved the maximum six years as\npresident under Jesuit rules.\nFather Keleher, a native of Wo\nburn and graduate of Holy Cross\nwaR ordained in 1937. He served af;\nassistant provincial in New England j\nfor three years and then becatnt\nmaster of novices at Shariowbrool:\nnovitate in Lenox.\nFather Healy is Holy Cross' young\nent president in Its 103-year hti\nlery, A native of South Boston,\nthe Worcester institution's 21st\npresident was ordained at Wee*\nton College In 1935 and Joined the\nfaculty at Shadowbroo* where he\nInter became deun of itudlte.\nBensen May Hood\nG.O.P. Committee\nfor the Republican ally\nconvention will be\nof the Republican\nan.\nseek T outn\nIn Officer's\nDeath\nBoston, Aug. 20\u2014(UP)\u2014A youth\nabout 21 years old was sought by\npolice today in the slaying of Army\nLt. John M. Falloni, 35, of Beverly,\nwho was strangled and robbed in\nhis ninth-floor, room at Hotel Stat\nler.\nAuthorities said the unidentified\nyouth was with Falloni when the\nformer school teacher, registered at\nthe hotel Saturday night. Members\nof the officer\u2019s family, whom he had\nbeen visiting at Beverly, said be\ncarried \u201ca large sum of money.\u201d\nStraggle Ensued\nHis empty wallet was found in the\nroom, which showed marks of\nterriffic struggle, and police said hie\nwrist watch was missing.\nMedical Examiner Timothy Leary\nsaid death was caused by strangu\nlation and finger marks on the\nvictim\u2019s necks indicated his assail-\nant strangled him with his hands.\nIt was the second slaying of a\nschool teacher and third attack on\na school\nmaster here in recent\nmonths. Chase Mac Arthur, Foxboro\nsuperint endent of schools, was killed\nin a Turkish bath, an$ George Daw\nson of Manhasset, L. I., was blud\ngeoned in a Beacon Hill hotel.\nEntered Together\nPolice quoted George Gorham, a\nbell boy, as saying that Falloni and\nthe unidentified youth entered the\nhotel together but that only the of\nficer registered. Both went to his\nroom but returned to the lobby\nwithin a few minutes and the vic\ntim was not seen again until his\nnude body was found by a watch\nman early yesterday.\nIn the room detectives found two\nwater glasses partly filled with\nwhiskey.\nOccupants of adjoining rooms\ntold police no unusual noises wewi\nheard. Falloni\u2019s room was only\nthree doors from the floor clerk's\ndesk.\nThe officer had been stationed at\nCamp Edwards, awaiting dlwbajf^^\nHe was graduated from Officers\u2019\nTraining School at Fort Belvoir, Va.,\nand served at Marfii Field, Cal., and.\nother posts as a camouflage in\nstructor during his three years to\nthe Army.\nCompensation\nAgreements\nCompensation Comm\nJohn J. O\u2019Connell today m\\\nthe following agreemer\nweekly payments during\nity:\u2014\nDavid Trueof of 116\nstreet against Waterbary\ncommittee, 630. beginning\nfracture at base of spine,\nJuly 29.\nNicholas Peruginl of 31 I\navenue against Americas\nCo., 628.70. beginning i\ncheat injury.\nEdward J. Simmons of\ntnck against T. F. Bwt\nlnc\u201e 621.07 beginning i\ncontusion of right thigh.","height":"28436","width":"20860"}}
